---
import WritingLayout from '../../layouts/WritingLayout.astro';
import { writingPosts } from '../../data/writing';

const post = writingPosts.find(p => p.slug === 'ai-flame-graphs')!;
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<WritingLayout post={post}>
  <figure class="my-8 rounded-xl overflow-hidden border border-[#27272A]">
    <img src={`${base}/images/writing/flame-graph.svg`} alt="Flame graph with LLM analysis overlay" class="w-full" loading="lazy"/>
    <figcaption class="px-4 py-2 bg-[#111115] text-xs text-[#52525B] text-center">Flame graph with inline LLM analysis — hot RSA verify path flagged automatically</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>The Problem with Flame Graphs</h2>
  <p>
    Flame graphs are one of the most information-dense debugging tools available. They're also
    opaque to anyone who didn't build the service. A 6-layer stack trace through a .NET runtime,
    an HTTP framework, three middleware layers, and your own code tells an expert exactly what's
    happening. It tells everyone else nothing.
  </p>
  <p>
    On-call engineers at 2am don't always have that expertise. And even experts spend time parsing
    the visualization before they start reasoning about the cause. We wanted to close that gap.
  </p>

  <h2>What We Built</h2>
  <p>
    We integrated the Grafana LLM plugin with Pyroscope to add an "Explain this flame graph"
    button in Grafana's Explore view. When clicked, it:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Extracts the top N hottest stack frames from the active profile query</li>
    <li>Sends them to a Claude API endpoint alongside service metadata (language, team, recent deploys)</li>
    <li>Streams the explanation back inline in the Grafana panel</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The result is a plain-English summary: what's running hot, likely cause, and suggested next steps.
    Not a replacement for reading the flame graph — a starting point for triage.
  </p>

  <h2>The Grafana LLM Plugin</h2>
  <p>
    The Grafana LLM plugin is an official Grafana Labs plugin that provides a standard interface for
    connecting Grafana to LLM backends. It handles auth, streaming, and a shared config so you don't
    need to embed API keys in every custom panel.
  </p>
  <p>
    Setup is straightforward: install the plugin, configure the LLM provider (OpenAI or a compatible
    API), and then call it from any panel using the plugin's JavaScript API. Pyroscope ≥1.5 is
    required for the flame graph data to be exposed in the right format.
  </p>

  <h2>The Prompt</h2>
  <p>
    The hard part wasn't the integration — it was the prompt. Raw stack frame names are not LLM-friendly.
    A frame like <code>System.Net.Http.HttpClientHandler.SendAsync</code> is meaningful to a .NET
    developer but needs context for the model to reason about it correctly.
  </p>
  <p>
    What worked: a structured prompt that includes the runtime, the top 10 frames by CPU percentage,
    the total profile duration, and a brief service description pulled from our Backstage catalog.
    The model then answers three questions:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>What is the hottest code path and what does it do?</li>
    <li>Is this pattern normal for this type of service, or does it look like a regression?</li>
    <li>What would you check next?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Constraining the output to those three questions cut hallucination rate significantly compared
    to open-ended prompts.
  </p>

  <h2>What It Gets Right</h2>
  <p>
    The LLM is good at explaining what a stack frame does in plain English, especially for well-known
    frameworks. "This call is allocating a new HTTP connection because the connection pool is
    exhausted" is the kind of summary that saves five minutes of Googling at 3am.
  </p>
  <p>
    It's also good at spotting anomalies when given baseline context. If the service description
    mentions "stateless API handler" and the flame graph shows 40% of CPU in serialization, the
    model flags that as unexpected.
  </p>

  <h2>What It Gets Wrong</h2>
  <p>
    Anything proprietary or internal. The model has no knowledge of your codebase. If the hottest
    frame is <code>OrderProcessor.ApplyDiscountRules</code>, it can describe it as "business logic
    applying discount calculations" but can't tell you whether that's regressed since the last deploy.
  </p>
  <p>
    We partially addressed this by including the git diff summary of recent deploys in the prompt.
    It's imperfect — the context window fills up fast — but it meaningfully improves explanations
    for post-deploy regressions.
  </p>

  <h2>Lessons</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Start with a constrained output format. Open-ended LLM summaries for technical data are noisy and hard to scan during an incident.</li>
    <li>Pull service context from your catalog (Backstage, PagerDuty, wherever). A flame graph without service context is half the information.</li>
    <li>Don't position it as "AI diagnosis" — engineers will over-trust it. Position it as "first read" and keep the raw flame graph prominent.</li>
    <li>Cache responses keyed by profile query + time window. Identical queries during an incident shouldn't burn API quota for the same result.</li>
  </ul>
</WritingLayout>
